16 (As enacted by Section 1 of this Act)
17 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
18 That Section(s) 23–802 through 23–812 of Article – Education of the Annotated Code of
19 Maryland be renumbered to be Section(s) 23–803 through 23–813, respectively.
20 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That the Laws of Maryland read
21 as follows:
22 Article – Education
23 23–801.
24 (a) In this subtitle the following words have the meanings indicated.
25 (h) (1) “Employee” means a full–time or part–time employee of the library.
26 (2) “Employee” does not include a confidential employee[,] OR
27 management employee[, or supervisory employee].
28 (k) “Management employee” means an employee who generally has authority and
29 who:
30 (1) Formulates policy that is applicable throughout a bargaining unit;
31 (2) Has a significant role in personnel administration, employee relations,
32 or the preparation and administration of budgets for the employer; or
33 (3) May reasonably be required to:

HOUSE BILL 388 3
1 (i) Assist directly in the preparation for and conduct of collective
2 bargaining negotiations on behalf of the employer; or
3 (ii) Have a major role in the administration of resulting collective
4 bargaining agreements.
5 (l) “Supervisory employee” means an employee who is authorized to:
6 (1) Hire, transfer, suspend, lay off, recall, promote, discharge, assign,
7 reward, or discipline employees;
8 (2) Responsibly direct employees for more than 50% of the employee’s
9 working hours; or
10 (3) Address and resolve the grievances of employees.
11 23–802.
12 (A) THERE MAY NOT BE MORE THAN TWO BARGAINING UNITS ESTABLISHED
13 UNDER THIS SUBTITLE, INCLUDING:
14 (1) ONE BARGAINING UNIT FOR EMPLOYEES WHO ARE NOT
15 SUPERVISORY EMPLOYEES; AND
16 (2) ONE BARGAINING UNIT FOR SUPERVISORY EMPLOYEES.
17 (B) THIS SUBTITLE MAY NOT BE CONSTRUED TO MODIFY OR TERMINATE:
18 (1) A BARGAINING UNIT THAT WAS RECOGNIZED OR IN EXISTENCE ON
19 OR BEFORE JUNE 30, 2026; OR
20 (2) A COLLECTIVE BARGAINING AGREEMENT ENTERED INTO ON OR
21 BEFORE JUNE 30, 2026.
22 23–803.
23 (a) An employee who may effectively recommend an action listed in [§ 23–801(l)]
24 § 23–801(K) of this subtitle may be deemed a [supervisory] MANAGEMENT employee if
25 the employee’s exercise of the authority requires the exercise of independent judgment and
26 is not merely of a routine or clerical nature.
27 (b) The exercise of any single function listed in [§ 23–801(l)] § 23–801(K) of this
28 subtitle may not necessarily require the conclusion that the individual exercising that

4 HOUSE BILL 388
1 function is in fact a [supervisory] MANAGEMENT employee within the meaning of the
2 definition.
3 (c) In differentiating a [supervisory] MANAGEMENT employee from a
4 [nonsupervisory] NONMANAGEMENT employee:
5 (1) A class title alone may not be the basis for determination; and
6 (2) The nature of the [supervisory] MANAGEMENT employee’s work,
7 including whether or not a significant portion of the [supervisory] MANAGEMENT
8 employee’s working time is spent as part of a team that includes [nonsupervisory]
9 NONMANAGEMENT employees shall be considered.
10 23–810.
11 (a) The Board shall submit a term of a collective bargaining agreement or
12 memorandum of understanding entered into under [§§ 23–807 and 23–808] §§ 23–808
13 AND 23–809 of this subtitle to the County Executive with the Board’s recommendation
14 regarding whether the agreement or the mediator’s decision requires an appropriation of
15 additional funds.
16 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
17 1, 2026.
Approved:
